        contentMd: "# Acute & Chronic Pancreatitis - Clinical\n\n## Acute Pancreatitis - Clinical Features\n### Presentation\n- Sudden onset severe epigastric pain radiating to back (pathognomonic)\n- Associated nausea, vomiting, tachycardia, fever\n- Mild cases: Leukocytosis, elevated enzymes\n- Severe cases: Shock, ARDS, acute kidney injury\n\n### Diagnosis\nRottterdam criteria: ≥2 of 3 features\n1. Characteristic abdominal pain (acute onset, epigastric, radiating to back)\n2. Serum lipase or amylase >3× ULN\n3. Characteristic imaging findings\n\n### Severity Assessment (Ranson Criteria - simplified)\nAt admission: Age >55, WBC >16,000, Glucose >200, AST >250, LDH >350\nAt 48 hours: Hematocrit drop >10%, BUN rise >5, Calcium <8, pO2 <60, Base deficit >4\nScore ≥3 = Severe\n\n## Chronic Pancreatitis - Clinical Features\n### Presentation\n- Chronic epigastric pain (often with alcohol)\n- Weight loss and malabsorption\n- Steatorrhea (greasy stools) and fat-soluble vitamin deficiencies\n- Secondary diabetes mellitus (\"pancreatogenic diabetes\")\n- Pancreatic calcification visible on imaging\n\n### Indian Context Considerations\n- Idiopathic chronic pancreatitis more common in younger patients in India\n- Tropical pancreatitis (associated with cassava consumption) is distinct entity\n- Genetic mutations (CFTR, SPINK1) should be considered\n\n## Diagnosis\n- Elevated lipase/amylase (acute phase)\n- Imaging: CT (gold standard for acute, shows necrosis extent); ERCP/MRI for ductal anatomy\n- In chronic disease: Pancreatic calcification on plain X-ray or CT\n- Low fecal chymotrypsin or 72-hour fecal fat >7g/day confirms malabsorption\n\n## Complications\nAcute: Acute kidney injury, Acute respiratory distress syndrome, Disseminated intravascular coagulation, Pancreatic necrosis, Infected necrosis, Pseudocyst formation\nChronic: Endocrine insufficiency (diabetes), Exocrine insufficiency (malabsorption), Pancreatic cancer (5× increased risk), Biliary obstruction, Splenic vein thrombosis\n\n## Management\n### Acute Pancreatitis\n- NPO status until pain resolves\n- IV fluid resuscitation (lactated Ringer's preferred over normal saline)\n- Analgesia (opioids if needed)\n- Antiemetics\n- Consider ERCP within 48 hours if cholangitis or biliary obstruction suspected\n- Antibiotics only if infected necrosis confirmed\n\n### Chronic Pancreatitis\n- Alcohol cessation mandatory\n- Fat-soluble vitamin supplementation (A, D, E, K)\n- Pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy (lipase, protease, amylase)\n- Management of secondary diabetes with conventional agents\n- Treatment of pain (difficult; may require interventional procedures or surgery)",
