        contentMd: "# Chronic Kidney Disease - Foundation\n\n## Definition\nChronic kidney disease (CKD) is defined as reduced kidney function (GFR <60 mL/min/1.73m²) or kidney damage (albuminuria ≥30 mg/day) for ≥3 months.\n\n## Epidemiology\n- Global prevalence: 10-15% of adult population\n- Leading cause of end-stage renal disease (ESRD) in India: Diabetes (40%), Hypertension (30%), Chronic glomerulonephritis (20%)\n- CKD affects 1 in 10 adults in developed countries; higher in India due to endemic infections and diabetes\n\n## Classification\n### KDIGO Classification (2012)\nGFR stages:\n- G1: ≥90 mL/min/1.73m²\n- G2: 60-89\n- G3a: 45-59\n- G3b: 30-44\n- G4: 15-29\n- G5: <15 (kidney failure)\n\nAlbuminuria stages (24-hour urine albumin):\n- A1: <30 mg/day (normal)\n- A2: 30-300 mg/day (microalbuminuria)\n- A3: >300 mg/day (macroalbuminuria)\n\n## Basic Pathophysiology\nInitial kidney injury → Nephron loss → Compensatory hyperfiltration in remaining nephrons → Progressive glomerulosclerosis → CKD progression\n\n## Common Causes\nDiabetic nephropathy, Hypertensive nephrosclerosis, Chronic glomerulonephritis (Post-infectious, IgA nephropathy, Lupus), Polycystic kidney disease, Obstructive uropathy, Recurrent pyelonephritis\n\n## Risk Factors for CKD Progression\nDiabetes, Hypertension, Proteinuria, Smoking, Obesity, Dyslipidemia, NSAIDs use",
