        summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, management of CKD, complications, and slowing progression in Indian healthcare context",
        contentMd: "# Chronic Kidney Disease - Clinical\n\n## Clinical Presentation\nEarly CKD (Stages 1-3): Often asymptomatic; discovered incidentally on routine labs\nAdvanced CKD (Stages 4-5): Symptoms of uremia develop (anemia, bone disease, hypertension, pericarditis)\n\n## Symptoms of Uremia\n- Fatigue (from anemia and uremic toxins)\n- Nausea, vomiting, anorexia\n- Cognitive dysfunction (uremic encephalopathy)\n- Neuropathy (peripheral, autonomic)\n- Pericarditis (can lead to tamponade)\n- Bleeding tendency\n- Muscle cramps\n\n## Diagnosis\n1. Serum creatinine (though influenced by age, sex, muscle mass - not ideal alone)\n2. eGFR calculation (MDRD equation or CKD-EPI preferred for Indian population)\n3. Urinalysis and urine protein quantification\n4. Renal imaging (ultrasound for structural disease, size)\n5. Biopsy if etiology unclear and would change management\n\n## Screening Recommendations\n- Diabetic patients: Annual microalbuminuria screening\n- Hypertensive patients: Baseline serum creatinine and urinalysis\n- High-risk groups: Family history of CKD/ESRD, obesity, smoking\n\n## Complications of CKD\n\n### Mineral-Bone Disorders\n- Secondary hyperparathyroidism (from phosphate retention, calcitriol deficiency)\n- Vascular calcification\n- Renal osteodystrophy\n- Increased fracture risk\n\n### Cardiovascular Complications\n- Hypertension (due to fluid overload and RAAS activation)\n- Left ventricular hypertrophy\n- Accelerated atherosclerosis\n- Arrhythmias (from hyperkalemia)\n\n### Hematologic Complications\n- Anemia (from reduced erythropoietin)\n- Bleeding tendency (uremic platelets)\n- Thrombosis risk (hypercoagulable state)\n\n### Metabolic Complications\n- Acidosis\n- Hyperkalemia (dangerous when GFR <15)\n- Hyponatremia\n- Hypocalcemia, hyperphosphatemia\n\n### Infections\n- Higher susceptibility (uremia impairs immunity)\n- Common in India: Tuberculosis reactivation, recurrent UTIs\n\n## Management Strategy\n\n### Slowing Progression\n1. Blood pressure control to <130/80 mmHg (more stringent in proteinuric CKD)\n2. ACE inhibitors or ARBs - first-line (reduce proteinuria and RAAS activation)\n3. SGLT2 inhibitors (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin) - slow progression regardless of diabetes status\n4. Weight loss if overweight\n5. Smoking cessation\n6. NSAIDs avoidance\n7. Glycemic control in diabetics\n\n### Treating Complications\n- Anemia: Iron supplementation, erythropoiesis-stimulating agents if Hb <10 g/dL\n- Bone disease: Phosphate binders, calcium supplementation, vitamin D analogues\n- Hypertension: Aim for <130/80 mmHg with multiple agents if needed\n- Hyperkalemia: Dietary restriction, diuretics, potassium binders (patiromer, sodium zirconium cyclosilicate)\n- Acidosis: Sodium bicarbonate if pH <7.2\n\n### Indian Context Considerations\n- Endemic infections (TB) common; screening essential\n- Limited access to expensive medications in some areas; generic ACE inhibitors/ARBs widely available\n- Traditional medicine practitioners still consulted; need patient education\n- Malnutrition common; adequate protein intake important until ESRD\n\n## Preparing for Renal Replacement Therapy\n- Fistula creation (AV fistula preferred over graft) when GFR ~15\n- Peritoneal dialysis training if suitable\n- Transplant evaluation and registry enrollment\n- Education about lifestyle changes with dialysis",
