        summary: "Comprehensive flashcards on CKD pathophysiology, complications, diagnostics, and management principles",
        contentMd: "# Chronic Kidney Disease - Active Recall Flashcards\n\n## Q&A Flashcards\n\nQ1: Define chronic kidney disease according to KDIGO 2012 criteria\nA: CKD is defined as GFR <60 mL/min/1.73m² OR evidence of kidney damage (albuminuria ≥30 mg/day, structural abnormalities) for ≥3 months\n\nQ2: What are the main causes of CKD in India?\nA: 1) Diabetes mellitus (40%), 2) Hypertension (30%), 3) Chronic glomerulonephritis (20%), 4) Others including infections, obstructive disease\n\nQ3: Explain the concept of hyperfiltration in CKD progression\nA: After nephron loss, remaining nephrons increase single-nephron GFR (hyperfiltration) to maintain total GFR. This increases glomerular pressure and perpetuates injury, accelerating sclerosis.\n\nQ4: How does proteinuria contribute to CKD progression mechanistically?\nA: Filtered proteins (albumin) reabsorbed by proximal tubule activate complement, release TGF-β and other pro-fibrotic cytokines, cause tubular epithelial toxicity and apoptosis.\n\nQ5: At what GFR stage does secondary hyperparathyroidism typically develop?\nA: Usually when GFR <45 mL/min (stage G3b-G4). Caused by phosphate retention, calcitriol deficiency, and FGF23 resistance.\n\nQ6: What is the mechanism of anemia in CKD?\nA: Reduced erythropoietin production due to decreased renal mass, and shortened RBC lifespan from uremic toxins. Develops at GFR <45.\n\nQ7: Compare the mechanisms by which ACE inhibitors and SGLT2 inhibitors reduce proteinuria\nA: ACE-I: Block angiotensin II → efferent arteriole vasoconstriction → reduced glomerular pressure → less proteinuria. SGLT2i: Osmotic diuresis → reduced intraglomerular pressure.\n\nQ8: Why is phosphate retention dangerous in CKD? What are complications?\nA: Hyperphosphatemia stimulates PTH secretion (secondary hyperparathyroidism), promotes vascular calcification, increases cardiovascular mortality.\n\nQ9: List the major complications of CKD at advanced stages\nA: Mineral-bone disease (hyperPTH, vascular calcification), Cardiovascular (HTN, LVH, atherosclerosis), Metabolic acidosis, Hyperkalemia, Anemia, Bleeding tendency, Infections\n\nQ10: What is the target blood pressure in CKD? Why?\nA: <130/80 mmHg (more stringent than non-CKD patients). Tight control reduces proteinuria, slows RAAS activation, and prevents cardiovascular complications.\n\nQ11: When is renal artery biopsy indicated in CKD workup?\nA: Rarely. Consider only when etiology unclear and would change management (e.g., suspected rapidly progressive GN). Serologies and imaging first-line.\n\nQ12: Describe the RAAS activation cycle in CKD and how ACE inhibitors interrupt it\nA: Nephron loss → decreased renal perfusion → renin release → angiotensin II increases → vasoconstriction, fibrosis, proteinuria. ACE-I blocks angiotensin II formation, breaking the cycle.",
        mnemonics: [],
        keyPoints: ["KDIGO classification combines GFR and albuminuria stages", "Hyperfiltration mechanism drives CKD progression in remaining nephrons", "ACE inhibitors and ARBs reduce both hemodynamic injury and fibrosis", "SGLT2 inhibitors now key therapy independent of diabetes status", "Secondary hyperparathyroidism develops at GFR <45", "Blood pressure target <130/80 mmHg to slow progression"],
