        contentMd: "# Adrenal Disorders - Exam Prep\n\n## High-Yield Facts\n1. 8 AM cortisol <5 µg/dL is diagnostic of adrenal insufficiency (any cause)\n2. ACTH >250 pg/mL indicates primary adrenal insufficiency\n3. ACTH <10 pg/mL indicates secondary insufficiency or ACTH-independent Cushing\n4. Low-dose dexamethasone (1 mg) suppresses cortisol in healthy subjects; failure suggests Cushing syndrome\n5. High-dose dexamethasone suppresses cortisol in Cushing disease but NOT in ectopic ACTH\n6. Hyponatremia is common in Addison disease (salt wasting); hyperkalemia also present\n7. Pituitary adenoma accounts for 70% of Cushing syndrome cases\n\n## NEXT-Pattern Questions\n\n### Problem Solving (60%)\nQ: Patient with fatigue, hypotension (100/60), hyponatremia (125 mEq/L), hyperkalemia (5.8 mEq/L). Suspect Addison disease. Initial test?\nA: 8 AM cortisol (if <5 µg/dL, diagnostic). Then ACTH level (elevated indicates primary Addison).\n\nQ: Obese woman with HTN, purple striae, proximal weakness, fasting glucose 145. 24-hour UFC elevated. High-dose DST shows suppression. Likely diagnosis?\nA: Cushing disease (pituitary adenoma). Suppression with HDDS distinguishes from ectopic ACTH. MRI pituitary to localize adenoma.\n\n### Analysis (30%)\nQ: Why does Addison disease cause hyperpigmentation while secondary adrenal insufficiency does not?\nA: In primary insufficiency, lack of negative feedback from cortisol allows ACTH elevation. ACTH is derived from pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC), which also produces melanocyte-stimulating hormone (MSH). Elevated MSH causes hyperpigmentation.\n\nQ: Explain why cortisol must be suppressed to <50% of baseline in high-dose DST for Cushing disease\nA: Normal feedback still intact in pituitary adenoma (though impaired). High doses of dexamethasone can eventually suppress ACTH from adenoma. Ectopic ACTH is autonomous and not suppressed by any dose of dexamethasone.\n\n### Recall (10%)\nQ: What is the mechanism of action of mitotane?\nA: Inhibits 11-beta-hydroxylase, blocking cortisol synthesis. Also adrenolytic (destroys adrenal tissue).\n\nQ: What is the first-line treatment for Cushing disease?\nA: Transsphenoidal pituitary surgery (80-90% remission)\n\n## Diagnostic Algorithms\n\nSuspected Addison → 8 AM cortisol → If <5: Measure ACTH → If >250: Primary insufficiency → Cosyntropin test confirms → Determine cause (TB, autoimmune workup)\n\nSuspected Cushing → 24-hour UFC or late-night salivary cortisol → If elevated, LDDST → If cortisol not suppressed: Measure ACTH → If elevated: HDDS (pituitary vs ectopic) → Imaging based on ACTH level\n\n## Common Exam Scenarios\n1. Acute hypotension with fever and abdominal pain in suspected Addison: Adrenal crisis; IV hydrocortisone 100 mg stat\n2. Incidental adrenal nodule with Cushing symptoms: Adrenal adenoma; consider adrenalectomy\n3. Small cell lung cancer with hypokalemia and elevated cortisol: Ectopic ACTH; medical management while treating cancer\n4. Post-adrenalectomy patient: Lifelong replacement (glucocorticoid + mineralocorticoid if bilateral removal)",
