        summary: "Pituitary anatomy, hormones, anterior/posterior pituitary disorders classification",
        contentMd: "# Pituitary Disorders - Foundation\n\n## Pituitary Anatomy\nSmall gland (0.5 cm diameter) at base of brain in sella turcica. Two components: Anterior (adenohypophysis) produces 6 hormones; Posterior (neurohypophysis) stores and releases 2 hormones.\n\n## Anterior Pituitary Hormones\n1. Growth hormone (GH) - somatotrophs (50%)\n2. Prolactin (PRL) - lactotrophs (20%)\n3. TSH - thyrotrophs (20%)\n4. ACTH - corticotrophs (10%)\n5. FSH and LH - gonadotrophs\n\n## Posterior Pituitary Hormones\n1. Vasopressin (ADH) - regulates water balance\n2. Oxytocin - milk letdown, uterine contractions\n\n## Classification of Disorders\n\n### Anterior Pituitary Disorders\n- GH excess: Acromegaly (somatotroph adenoma)\n- GH deficiency: Short stature, loss of muscle/bone\n- Prolactin excess: Lactotroph adenoma\n- TSH/ACTH deficiency: Secondary hypothyroidism/insufficiency\n\n### Posterior Pituitary Disorders\n- Diabetes insipidus (ADH deficiency or resistance)\n- SIADH (ADH excess)\n\n### Pituitary Tumors\n- Adenomas (95% of pituitary tumors)\n- Prolactinoma (40% of adenomas)\n- Growth hormone-secreting (20%)\n- Non-functioning adenomas (30%)\n- ACTH-secreting (Cushing disease, 10%)\n- TSH-secreting (rare)\n\n## Epidemiology\n- Pituitary adenomas: 1:1000 autopsy prevalence; 100 cases per million clinically significant\n- Prolactinoma most common functioning adenoma\n- Acromegaly 3-4 cases per million\n- Hypopituitarism from adenoma, post-surgery, trauma, apoplexy, radiation",
