        summary: "Pathophysiology of pituitary adenomas, hormone excess/deficiency syndromes, and mass effects",
        contentMd: "# Pituitary Disorders - Mechanism\n\n## Pituitary Adenoma Development\n- Loss of tumor suppressor genes (p53, menin in MEN-1)\n- Somatic mutations in GNAS (acromegaly), PRKAR1A\n- Monoclonal origin (single cell transformation)\n- Grow slowly; 5-10% become large enough for symptoms at diagnosis\n- Compressive effects: Optic chiasm compression → visual field defects; cavernous sinus involvement → cranial nerve palsies\n\n## Prolactinoma Pathophysiology\n- Lactotroph adenoma constitutively secreting prolactin\n- Loss of dopamine inhibition (dopamine is prolactin-inhibiting factor from hypothalamus)\n- Elevated prolactin inhibits GnRH → hypogonadism\n- May cause stalk effect (mass compression raising prolactin mildly)\n\n## Acromegaly (GH Excess)\n- Somatotroph adenoma autonomous GH secretion\n- GH stimulates IGF-1 production (liver, peripheral tissues)\n- IGF-1 causes somatic growth, metabolic effects\n- Glucose intolerance, hypertension, cardiac hypertrophy, arthropathy\n- Neoplasia risk (colorectal cancer)\n\n## Hypopituitarism from Adenoma\n- Mass compression → stalk compression → loss of trophic hormone stimulation\n- Order of hormone loss typically: GH (first), LH/FSH, ACTH, TSH (last)\n- Prolactin may paradoxically rise (lost dopaminergic inhibition)\n- Anterior pituitary often functions normally if not directly invaded\n\n## Mass Effect Complications\n- Optic chiasm compression: Bitemporal hemianopsia (nasal fields lost first)\n- Invasion into cavernous sinus: CN III, IV, VI palsy, V1/V2 involvement\n- Apoplexy (hemorrhage/infarction): Sudden headache, visual loss, pituitary failure",
