        summary: "Diagnostic algorithms, hormone testing strategies, and management decision trees for pituitary disease",
        contentMd: "# Pituitary Disorders - Exam Prep\n\n## High-Yield Facts\n1. Prolactinoma is 40% of pituitary adenomas (most common functioning type)\n2. Prolactin >200 ng/mL strongly suggests prolactinoma\n3. GH should suppress <1 µg/L after 75g OGTT (failure indicates acromegaly)\n4. IGF-1 elevation confirms GH excess (more reliable than GH level)\n5. Bitemporal hemianopsia from optic chiasm compression\n6. Dopamine agonists shrink prolactinoma in 80-90% (first-line medical therapy)\n7. Transsphenoidal surgery gold standard for acromegaly\n8. Pituitary apoplexy causes sudden severe headache, vision loss, pituitary failure\n\n## NEXT-Pattern Questions\n\n### Problem Solving (60%)\nQ: Woman with amenorrhea, galactorrhea, prolactin 250 ng/mL. MRI shows 8mm adenoma. Management?\nA: Start dopamine agonist (cabergoline 0.25 mg BID). Monitor prolactin, menses, visual fields every 6 months. Surgery only if agonist fails or acute vision change.\n\nQ: Man with coarse features, large hands, IGF-1 elevated, GH 8 µg/L (fails to suppress <1 on OGTT). 20mm somatotroph adenoma on MRI. Treatment?\nA: Transsphenoidal surgery (first-line). If post-op GH still >2 µg/L, add somatostatin analog or GH receptor antagonist.\n\n### Analysis (30%)\nQ: Why does mass compression of pituitary stalk cause prolactin elevation?\nA: Dopamine (prolactin-inhibiting factor) is released from hypothalamus via hypophyseal portal blood. Stalk compression disrupts dopamine delivery → loss of tonic prolactin suppression → elevation.\n\nQ: Distinguish GH suppression patterns in normal vs acromegaly after OGTT\nA: Normal: GH suppresses <1 µg/L, IGF-1 normal. Acromegaly: GH remains >2-5 µg/L despite elevated glucose (failure of suppression), IGF-1 markedly elevated.\n\n### Recall (10%)\nQ: What is the first-line medical treatment for prolactinoma?\nA: Dopamine agonists (cabergoline or bromocriptine)\n\nQ: What visual field defect results from optic chiasm compression?\nA: Bitemporal hemianopsia (loss of nasal/temporal fields bilaterally)\n\n## Diagnostic Algorithms\n\nSuspected pituitary adenoma → MRI pituitary (visualizes tumor) → Measure hormonal excess (prolactin, IGF-1, ACTH, TSH depending on suspected type) → Assess for hypopituitarism (basal cortisol, free T4, testosterone/estrogen) → Visual field testing if tumor large\n\n## Common Exam Scenarios\n1. Prolactinoma with dopamine agonist resistance: Consider transsphenoidal surgery\n2. Acromegaly post-surgery with persistent elevation: Add somatostatin analog\n3. Mass effect with apoplexy: Emergent transsphenoidal decompression\n4. Hypopituitarism: Replace deficient hormones (GH, cortisol, thyroid, gonadal)",
