        summary: "Comprehensive flashcards on pituitary adenomas, hormone excess/deficiency, and management strategies",
        contentMd: "# Pituitary Disorders - Active Recall Flashcards\n\n## Q&A Flashcards\n\nQ1: What is the most common functioning pituitary adenoma and why?\nA: Prolactinoma (40% of adenomas). Lactotroph adenomas secrete prolactin autonomously, escaping dopamine inhibition from hypothalamus.\n\nQ2: Explain the mechanism by which prolactin elevation causes amenorrhea\nA: Elevated prolactin inhibits GnRH (gonadotropin-releasing hormone) release from hypothalamus → decreased LH/FSH → reduced estrogen production → amenorrhea.\n\nQ3: What is the difference between stalk effect and true prolactinoma?\nA: Stalk effect: Mass compression → loss of dopamine inhibition → prolactin <200 ng/mL. True prolactinoma: Adenoma secretes prolactin → prolactin >200 ng/mL (though overlap exists).\n\nQ4: Explain the pathophysiology of acromegaly (GH excess)\nA: Somatotroph adenoma produces GH autonomously. GH stimulates peripheral tissue production of IGF-1. IGF-1 causes skeletal growth (beyond epiphyseal closure → acromegaly), glucose intolerance, cardiac hypertrophy.\n\nQ5: What is the significance of IGF-1 elevation in acromegaly and why is it a better marker than GH?\nA: IGF-1 elevation more specific for GH excess (GH fluctuates; IGF-1 relatively stable). IGF-1 mediates growth effects of GH (skeletal growth, metabolic changes).\n\nQ6: How does optic chiasm compression from pituitary tumor cause bitemporal hemianopsia?\nA: Tumor grows upward from sella turcica, compressing nasal fibers of optic chiasm (these fibers decussate and represent nasal/temporal visual fields bilaterally).\n\nQ7: Describe the typical order of hormone loss when pituitary adenoma causes compression\nA: GH (lost first) → LH/FSH → ACTH → TSH (lost last). Prolactin may paradoxically rise (stalk compression removes dopamine inhibition).\n\nQ8: What is the first-line medical treatment for prolactinoma and why is it preferred over surgery?\nA: Dopamine agonists (cabergoline, bromocriptine). Shrink tumor in 80-90%, reverses hormonal symptoms, fewer complications than surgery (nerve injuries, CSF leak, hypopituitarism from surgical damage).\n\nQ9: What is the failure of GH suppression test in acromegaly and what is the normal response?\nA: Normal: GH <1 µg/L after 75g oral glucose. Acromegaly: GH remains >2-5 µg/L; failure of normal suppression is characteristic.\n\nQ10: Explain pituitary apoplexy: what is it and what are the consequences?\nA: Hemorrhage or infarction within pituitary adenoma. Presents with severe headache, vision loss, pituitary hormone deficiencies. Medical emergency; mortality ~1% but significant morbidity if delayed treatment.\n\nQ11: How is hypopituitarism from adenoma managed in terms of hormone replacement?\nA: Replace deficient hormones: GH if deficient (0.3-0.5 IU/kg/week), Glucocorticoids if ACTH deficient (hydrocortisone 15-20 mg daily), Thyroid hormone if TSH deficient (levothyroxine), Gonadal hormones if LH/FSH deficient (testosterone/estrogen+progesterone).\n\nQ12: What are the indications for surgical treatment of prolactinoma despite dopamine agonist availability?\nA: 1) Agonist resistance/intolerance, 2) Acute vision loss (emergency), 3) Pituitary apoplexy, 4) Patient preference for definitive treatment, 5) Large tumor with apoplexy risk.",
